// Razorpay technical round:
void processPayments(List<Payment> payments) {
    Collections.sort(payments, Comparator.comparing(p -> p.merchantId));
    Map<String, List<Payment>> byMerchant = new HashMap<>();
    for (Payment p : payments) {
        byMerchant.computeIfAbsent(p.merchantId, k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(p);
    }
    for (var entry : byMerchant.entrySet()) {
        reconcile(entry.getValue()); // O(m log m) where m = merchant's payment count
    }
}
// Interviewer: What is the time complexity?
// Wrong answer: 'O(n²)' — nervous guess
// Right answer: 'O(n log n) — dominated by the initial sort; the map building
// and per-merchant reconcile are collectively O(n log n) in the worst case'
```

concept_explanation.systematic_approach:
**5-step framework for any code:**

```
Step 1: Identify all loops and recursive calls
Step 2: For each loop, determine iterations in terms of n
Step 3: For nested structures: multiply; for sequential: add
Step 4: For recursion: write recurrence → solve (or use Master Theorem)
Step 5: Drop constants and non-dominant terms → Big-O

Example:
void example(int[] arr) {
    // Step 1: sort + loop + inner search
    Arrays.sort(arr);                           // O(n log n)
    for (int x : arr) {                         // O(n) iterations
        int idx = Arrays.binarySearch(arr, x);  // O(log n) each
    }
    // Step 2: sort=O(n log n), loop=O(n), each iteration=O(log n)
    // Step 3: sequential: O(n log n) + O(n × log n) = O(n log n) + O(n log n)
    // Step 5: O(n log n) — both terms are equal dominance
}
```

concept_explanation.recurrence_relations:
**Recursive complexity via recurrence:**

```java
// Binary search:
int search(int[] arr, int lo, int hi, int target) {
    if (lo > hi) return -1;
    int mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2;
    if (arr[mid] == target) return mid;
    if (arr[mid] < target) return search(arr, mid+1, hi, target); // half
    return search(arr, lo, mid-1, target);                         // half
}
// Recurrence: T(n) = T(n/2) + O(1)
// T(n) = T(n/4) + O(1) + O(1) = T(n/8) + 3O(1) = ... = O(log n) ✓

// Merge sort:
void mergeSort(int[] arr, int l, int r) {
    if (l >= r) return;
    int mid = l + (r - l) / 2;
    mergeSort(arr, l, mid);       // T(n/2)
    mergeSort(arr, mid+1, r);    // T(n/2)
    merge(arr, l, mid, r);       // O(n)
}
// Recurrence: T(n) = 2T(n/2) + O(n) → O(n log n) ✓
```

